## Middleware Conventions

Middleware uses chi's standard signature: `func(http.Handler) http.Handler`

Register globally in `main.go`, not sprinkled per-route unless route-specific:
```go
r.Use(middleware.RequestID)
r.Use(middleware.Recoverer)
r.Use(middleware.RealIP)
r.Use(middleware.Logger)       // structured slog adapter
r.Use(middleware.Timeout(30 * time.Second))
```

---

## Error Response Helper

Keep one `respondError` helper and use it everywhere:
```go
func respondError(w http.ResponseWriter, status int, title string, err error) {
    slog.Error("request error", "status", status, "title", title, "err", err)
    w.Header().Set("Content-Type", "application/problem+json")
    w.WriteHeader(status)
    json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(ProblemDetail{
        Type:   fmt.Sprintf("/errors/%s", slug(title)),
        Title:  title,
        Status: status,
        Detail: err.Error(),
    })
}
```

---

## Context Timeouts

Set timeouts at the handler level, never deep in the stack:
```go
ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(r.Context(), 10*time.Second)
defer cancel()
```

For heavy dashboard queries, be explicit: 30s timeout with a comment explaining why.

---

## JSON / Struct Tags

```go
type MetricRow struct {
    ID        uuid.UUID `json:"id"         db:"id"`
    Name      string    `json:"name"       db:"name"`
    Value     float64   `json:"value"      db:"value"`
    CreatedAt time.Time `json:"created_at" db:"created_at"`
}
```

Always use both `json` and `db` tags. Never `json:"-"` on fields that belong in the API response.

---

## Do Not

- Do not use `interface{}` or `any` in public API surfaces — define concrete types
- Do not use `init()` functions
- Do not use global mutable state
- Do not use `panic` for error flows — only for unrecoverable startup failures
- Do not use ORM "magic" methods that hide the SQL being generated
- Do not return naked `500` errors — always wrap with context before surfacing
